t=\"3120\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/d0JO7JPl.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"4208\" height=\"3120\" /></p>','Breaking ground.','','inherit','open','open','','27-revision-v1','','','2014-10-29 13:58:40','2014-10-29 13:58:40','',27,'http://localhost/?p=69',0,'revision','',0),(70,1,'2014-10-29 14:00:33','2014-10-29 14:00:33','Before I get started on the trailer itself, it needs a nice bed to rest on.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">First, to choose a location. Considering the best use of the yard, as well as the place easiest to maneuver the Airstream into, the south side seemed best. This would allow the awning to be used in its full glory (pics eventually) across the yard, and the trailer would separate the two properties, functioning like a privacy fence. <img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/DCjr08Il.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\nInitially the idea was to pour a concrete pad for the Airstream to rest on. But during the clearing and tilling of the yard we found a significant number of old bricks in decent condition that would work just as well. Not to mention they would give the spot a bit of charm, who doesn\'t like re-purposed bricks? Behold the aftermath of junk stone and brick.\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/pzG7Ugll.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">So, a spot was measured, 6ft by 8ft plot for the bricks to be laid. Tilled it, smoothed it, stomped it and started putting the clay down. Turns out there was roughly a third of the bricks required for the job, but bricks are not hard to come by from many of the crumbling buildings in south St. Louis. Below are a couple pictures of the unfinished pad, which will be completed, leveled and sanded in a future post. The trailer is getting closer to being in position and almost ready for the pulling and striping of the innards. <img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"https://i.imgur.com/fzr4TMql.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\